---
scope: src/bin
description: CLI entry point — parses input, orchestrates the fetch/score/render pipeline, and maps all outcomes to exit codes
intent: >
  The bin module is the user-facing shell of pkg-pulse. A developer runs
  `pkg-pulse <package-name>` and expects either a formatted health report
  printed to stdout and a clean exit, or a clear error message on stderr and
  a meaningful exit code they can act on or script against. This module owns
  nothing except the seam between the operating system and the rest of the
  pipeline: it validates input, wires the three internal stages together,
  handles every error path, and exits with the correct code. Success means
  the user never has to read source code to understand what went wrong.
outcomes:
  desired:
    - A valid package name produces a rendered health report on stdout and exits 0.
    - An invalid package name produces a usage-oriented message on stderr and exits 3 without making any network calls.
    - A package that does not exist on the registry produces a descriptive message on stderr and exits 1.
    - A total network failure produces a descriptive message on stderr and exits 2.
    - Running without a GITHUB_TOKEN emits a rate-limit warning to stderr and continues — it does not abort the run.
  undesired:
    - Swallowing an error silently and exiting 0 with an empty or partial report.
    - Writing error messages to stdout, which corrupts the report in scripted pipelines.
    - Using a single catch-all exit code for all failure modes, making the CLI unscriptable.
    - Performing network calls before input validation completes.
    - Treating a missing GITHUB_TOKEN as a fatal error rather than a degraded-mode warning.
---

